                    <div class="box-body">
                        <p>NickelTracker is a very simple tool that combines the <em>Envelope Budget</em> methodology
                        with a very basic expense tracker.</p>
                        <p>The purpose of the Envelope Budget methodology is to help you plan your monthly expenses and
                            divide them into categories, so you can assign a budget to each one and keep away the
                            money you'll be needing to cover each of those expenses. This way, you won't spend your payroll
                            on stuff that is unplanned or unneeded.</p>
                        <p>On the other hand, the expense tracker helps you keep a log of where you are spending your money.
                            NickelTracker is not automated in any way and is not linked to any banking institution, which
                            means that you'll have to be disciplined and record manually each and every transaction you
                            make.</p>
                        <p>NickelTracker is not, nor attempts to be, a financial adviser. It should be though of as a
                            friendly and simple tool to help you manage your finances and make informed decisions about
                            your money.</p>

                        <h4>Objects</h4>
                        <p>The system uses 3 core <em>objects</em> or concepts to record and track your budget and expenses.
                        You should deeply understand each of these concepts before using NickelTracker.</p>
                        <ul>
                            <li><strong>Accounts</strong> are where your money is stored or kept. They can be one of these types:
                            <ul>
                                <li>Cash: all your money that is not on the bank.</li>
                                <li>Debit: regular checking accounts in the bank.</li>
                                <li>Savings: pretty much like a Debit account, but it is meant to keep your money as a long-term
                                saving or investment.</li>
                                <li>Credit: all bank credit cards and service cards (this account type's balance is usually negative).</li>
                                <li>Coupon: employee benefits card / wallet for groceries and such.</li>
                                <li>Loaned: to keep records of the money you loan to or borrow from your friends.</li>
                            </ul>
                            </li>
                            <li><strong>Categories</strong> are only used for expenses and they are the basis for creating
                            your budget.</li>
                            <li><strong>Transactions</strong> are the core component of the system since they record your
                                payments, purchases, expenses, investments, loans, etc.
                                <ul>
                                    <li>Income: the money you earn</li>
                                    <li>Expense: the money you spend</li>
                                    <li>Transfer: movements of money between your own accounts</li>
                                </ul>
                            </li>
                        </ul>
                    </div>
